In my case (see ticket description), the test is parameterized. Some of the instances are short, and some of them are long:

```java
  public static Iterable<Object[]> data() {
    final StringBuilder reallyLongString = new StringBuilder(1024 * 1024);
    for (int i = 0; i < 185000; ++i) {
      reallyLongString.append(i);
    }

    final List<String> strings = new ArrayList<String>(150);
    strings.add("short simple"); // <-- this is short
    strings.add("longer but still not really all that long"); // <-- this is short as well
    strings.add(reallyLongString.toString());  // <-- this is LONG
```

That is why I think it is better to implement truncation (with a hash for keeping test names unique) rather than "fail on long test names".

Well, an alternative way could be to enhance `string={1}` like `string={1 | truncateTo(50)}` or something like that. However, I don't like making `{N}` syntax complicated as it would be hard to write.
